## What happened

Starting in .NET 11 (following the pattern set earlier in the ecosystem), **`DSA.Create()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` on macOS** (and iOS/tvOS). This is because:

1. .NET on Apple platforms uses Apple's **Security.framework** for cryptography.
2. Apple's framework **does not support DSA** — it was never implemented there.
3. Previously, .NET shipped an OpenSSL-based shim on macOS to fill the gap. That fallback has been removed.

Linux and Windows are unaffected because they have native DSA support (OpenSSL and CNG respectively).

## How to fix it

Since you only need to **verify** legacy signatures (not produce new ones), the cleanest fix is to use **BouncyCastle**, which is a fully managed (pure C#) cryptography library — no native OS dependency:

```bash
dotnet add package BouncyCastle.Cryptography
```

Then replace the platform-dependent call:

```csharp
// ❌ Before — throws on macOS/.NET 11
using var dsa = DSA.Create();
dsa.ImportSubjectPublicKeyInfo(publicKeyBytes, out _);
bool valid = dsa.VerifyData(data, signature, HashAlgorithmName.SHA1);
```

```csharp
// ✅ After — works everywhere (managed implementation)
using Org.BouncyCastle.Crypto.Parameters;
using Org.BouncyCastle.Security;

var publicKey = PublicKeyFactory.CreateKey(publicKeyBytes);
var verifier = SignerUtilities.GetSigner("SHA1withDSA");
verifier.Init(forSigning: false, publicKey);
verifier.BlockUpdate(data, 0, data.Length);
bool valid = verifier.VerifySignature(signature);
```

## Other options

| Approach | Pros | Cons |
|---|---|---|
| **BouncyCastle** (recommended) | Fully managed, cross-platform, drop-in | Extra dependency (~3 MB) |
| Ship OpenSSL on macOS via P/Invoke | No new managed dependency | You own the native binary lifecycle |
| Migrate signatures to ECDSA/RSA | Modern, supported everywhere | Requires re-signing all legacy data |

**Bottom line**: DSA is deprecated industry-wide. Use BouncyCastle to keep verifying legacy signatures cross-platform, and plan a migration to ECDSA or RSA for any new signing needs.
